---

âœ… So, your answer:

> When an error is thrown (using throw), JavaScript stops executing the current block immediately.
If the throw is not inside a try, the program stops completely.
If itâ€™s inside a try, the control jumps to the catch block, skips the remaining lines inside try, and continues after catch.




